Project Background¶

In 2000, Enron was one of the largest companies in the United States. By 2002, it had collapsed into bankruptcy due to widespread corporate fraud. In the resulting Federal investigation, a significant amount of typically confidential information entered into the public record, including tens of thousands of emails and detailed financial data for top executives. In this project, I will build a machine learning person of interest identifier (classifier) based on financial and email data made public as a result of the Enron scandal.

Task #3 : Feature Engineering ¶

[TOC](#TableOfContents#AutomatedFeatureSelectionSection)

Feature Reduction - Thirteen features were selected which significantly contributed to the classification process using SKLearn's SelectKBest feature picking algorithm. The other attributes were removed from the dataframe, leaving only these.

[TOC](#TableOfContents#ClassLabelsBallanceCheckSection)

Oversampling - There are only eighteen positive cases of POI's in the dataset of 140+ overall cases. This is a classical case of imbalanced class data which leads to poor classification performance. There are many ways to address this condition, the simplest is to employ oversampling, meaning to add in copies of the positive data to give the algorithm more viewings of what a positive case might look like.

[TOC](#TableOfContents#FeatureReductionSection)

  • SubTask: Create Validation Dataset

It is a good idea to use a validation hold-out set. This is a sample of the data that is held back from our analysis and modeling. It's right at the end of our project to confirm the accuracy of our final model. We will use 80% of the dataset for modeling and hold back 20% for validation.

[TOC](#TableOfContents#EvaluateClassifiersDescription)

Task #4 : Evaluate Classifiers¶

One doesn't know what algorithms will do well on this dataset. First appearances suggest distance based algorithms like K-Nearest Neighbors and Support Vector Machines may do well, but also rule based algorithms such as Decision Trees might perform well also.

The test harnass consists of a 10-fold cross validation. The dataset is not too small and this is a good standard test harness configuration. Algorithms are evaluated using the simple accuracy metric. This is a gross metric that will give a quick idea of how correct a given model is.

Selected aare a suite of different algorithms capable of working on this type of (Binary) classification problem.

The six algorithms selected include:

Linear Algorithms:

  • Logistic Regression (LR)

  • Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)

Nonlinear Algorithms:

  • Classiffcation and Regression Trees (CART)

  • Support Vector Machines (SVM)

  • Gaussian Naive Bayes (NB)

  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)

NOTE: All Algorithns are tested on "regular" data and "standardized" data.

It is suspected that the differing distributions of the raw data may be negatively impacting the performance of some of the algorithms, so the algorithms are re-evaluated with a standardized copy of the dataset, meaning the input data is transformed such that each attribute has a mean value of zero and a standard deviation of one.

We also need to avoid data leakage when we transform the data. A good way to avoid leakage is to use pipelines that standardize the data and build the model for each fold within the cross validation test harness.

Task #5 : Tune Classifiers¶

TASK: Achieve better than .3 Precision and .3 Recall using the test script.

  • It is very likely that configuration beyond the default may yield even more accurate models. We'll execute a grid search for the optimal parameter set and print out the best candidates.

Only those algorithms which have proven worthy to investigate further are included in the tuning process, those are:

  • LDA - Linear Discriminant Analysis

  • KNN - K Nearest Neighbors

  • SVM - Support Vector Machines

  • CART - Classiffcation and Regression Trees

NOTE: The tuning harnass consists of a 10 fold cross validation, with standardized data

  • SubTask: Ensemble Methods - Benchmarking
  • Five different ensemble machine learning algorithms are evaluated, two boosting and two bagging methods:

Boosting Methods: - Building multiple models (typically of the same type) from difierent subsamples of the training dataset.

  • AdaBoost (AB)

  • Gradient Boosting (GBM)

Bagging Methods: - Building multiple models (typically of the same type) each of which learns to fix the prediction errors of a prior model in the sequence of models.

  • Random Forests (RF)

  • Extra Trees (ET)

  • Bagging (BG)

NOTE: We will use the same test harness as before, 10-fold cross validation.

  • SubTask: Finalize Models

    Each of the models selected for performance will be finalized (run on validation data)

  • Finalize Singleton Models
  • KNN
  • SVM
  • CART
  • Finalize Ensemble Models

  • BaggingClassifier => DecisionTreeClassifier

  • ExtraTreesClassifier => KNN

    • Grid Search For Tuning ETC

Create new features using intuition alone.¶

There are 3 engineered features below "ratio_to", "ratio_from" and "big_shot". The "ratio_to", "ratio_from" features both deal with email to and from POI's whereas the "big_shot" is a combination of "Highly Paid" and "High Net Worth".

  • The idea is that a POI is most likely to have contributing attributes of a "Big Shot" which will likely contribute to successfully categorizing POI's.
In [42]:
Highly_Paid = mydataset['salary'] + mydataset['bonus'] + mydataset['loan_advances'] + mydataset['other']
In [43]:
High_Net_Worth = mydataset['exercised_stock_options'] + mydataset['restricted_stock']
In [44]:
big_shot = Highly_Paid + High_Net_Worth
In [45]:
mydataset['big_shot'] = big_shot
In [46]:
mydataset['ratio_to'] = mydataset['from_this_person_to_poi'] / mydataset['to_messages']
In [47]:
mydataset['ratio_from']= mydataset['from_poi_to_this_person'] / mydataset['from_messages']

Validation Dataset Extraction¶

It is a good idea to use a validation hold-out set. This is a sample of the data that we hold back from our analysis and modeling. We use it right at the end of our project to confirm the accuracy of our final model.

It is a smoke test that we can use to see if we messed up and to give us confidence on our estimates of accuracy on unseen data. We will use 80% of the dataset for modeling and hold back 20% for validation.

Validation Dataset (1a) - Raw 21 Atrribute Feature Set => OVERSAMPLED Dataset¶

In [54]:
# Split-out validation dataset (21 Attribute Feature Set)

array = over_sampled_df.values

# separate array into input and output components

X = array[:,0:20].astype(float) # NOTE: There are 23 columns, the category class is the 23rd, therefore exclude it.
Y = array[:,20]                 # NOTE: This is the isolated output class (or the 21st column)

validation_size = 0.20          # Validation Set Size 20%
seed = 7                        # Seed of 7 - for repeatability

# Split into train / validation sets 
X_train, X_validation, Y_train, Y_validation = cross_validation.train_test_split(X, Y,
    test_size=validation_size, random_state=seed)

SelectKBest¶

In [70]:
# Feature Extraction with Univariate Statistical Tests (Chi-squared for classification)

from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest
from sklearn.feature_selection import chi2


# feature extraction  using the chi-squared (chi2) statistical test for non-negative features.
# http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.feature_selection.SelectKBest.html#sklearn.feature_selection.SelectKBest
# http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/feature_selection.html#univariate-feature-selection
#
featureSelector  = SelectKBest(score_func=chi2, k=15)
fit = featureSelector .fit(X, Y)

# summarize scores
numpy.set_printoptions(precision=3)
print "SCORES: \n", fit.scores_

print "\n"

assumed_to_be_the_feature_ids_of_the_top_k_features = list(featureSelector.get_support(indices=True)) 
print "Choosen Feature IDs: ", assumed_to_be_the_feature_ids_of_the_top_k_features

print "\n"
features = fit.transform(X)

# summarize selected features
print "FEATURES: \n", features[0:20,:]


# You can see the scores for each attribute and the X attributes chosen
# (those with the HIGHEST scores chi^2 scores or highest selection score)
#
# I got the names for the chosen attributes by manually mapping the index of the 
# X HIGHEST chi scores (but highest index scores) to the index of the attribute names.

Task 4 - Evaluate Classifiers¶

Evaluate Algorithms: Baseline - no standardizing or normalizing of data (yet)¶

We don't know what algorithms will do well on this dataset. Gut feel suggests distance based algorithms like K-Nearest Neighbors and Support Vector Machines may do well, but also rule based algorithms such as Decision Trees.

Designing the test harness, we will use 10-fold cross validation. The dataset is not too small and this is a good standard test harness configuration. We will evaluate algorithms using the accuracy metric. This is a gross metric that will give a quick idea of how correct a given model is.

  • More useful on binary classification problems like this one.
In [79]:
# Test options and evaluation metric - used OFTEN later on - these are effectively CONSTANTS

num_folds = 10
num_instances = len(X_train)
seed = 7
scoring = 'accuracy' # This is a gross metric that will give a quick idea of how correct a given model is.

Let's create a baseline of performance on this problem and spot-check a number of different algorithms. We will select a suite of different algorithms capable of working on this (Binary type) classification problem.

The six algorithms selected include:

Linear Algorithms:

  • Logistic Regression (LR)

  • Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)

Nonlinear Algorithms:

  • Classiffcation and Regression Trees (CART)

  • Support Vector Machines (SVM)

  • Gaussian Naive Bayes (NB)

  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)

In [80]:
# Construct Algorithms List

models = []
models.append(('LR', LogisticRegression()))
models.append(('LDA', LinearDiscriminantAnalysis()))
models.append(('KNN', KNeighborsClassifier()))
models.append(('CART', DecisionTreeClassifier()))
models.append(('NB', GaussianNB()))
models.append(('SVM', SVC()))

[TOC](#TableOfContents#EvaluateClassifiersDescription)

Compare Baseline Algorithms¶

The algorithms all use default tuning parameters. Let's compare the algorithms. We will display the mean and standard deviation of accuracy for each algorithm as we calculate it and collect the results for use later.

In [81]:
# Execute them using Default Tuning Parameters ... 

results = []
names = []
for name, model in models:
    kfold = cross_validation.KFold(n=num_instances, n_folds=num_folds, random_state=seed)
    cv_results = cross_validation.cross_val_score(model, X_train, Y_train, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: MEAN: %f STD: (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)

Evaluate Algorithms: Standardize Data¶

We suspect that the differing distributions of the raw data may be negatively impacting the performance of some of the algorithms, so we'll scale the input to a standard. Any algorithm preferring input features in a normal distribution are targets for scaling.

  • Note: - I'll evaluate the same algorithms with a standardized input copy. Since this is section is intended to be an apples to apples comparison, I will use feature scaling even if some algorithms might not require it (aka : DecisionTreeClassifier), although most will benefit from scaling, such as:

LogisticRegression

LinearDiscriminantAnalysis

KNeighborsClassifier

GaussianNB

SVC

  • there are those which do not specifically require it:

    DecisionTreeClassifier

This is where the data is transformed such that each attribute has a mean value of zero and a standard deviation of one.

We also need to avoid data leakage when we transform the data. A good way to avoid leakage is to use pipelines that standardize the data and build the model for each fold in the cross validation test harness.

  • That way we can get a fair estimation of how each model with standardized data might perform on unseen data.
In [83]:
# Eestablish the pipelines for testing against standardized data

pipelines = []
pipelines.append(('ScaledLR', Pipeline([('Scaler', StandardScaler()),('LR',LogisticRegression())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledLDA', Pipeline([('Scaler', StandardScaler()),('LDA',LinearDiscriminantAnalysis())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledKNN', Pipeline([('Scaler', StandardScaler()),('KNN',KNeighborsClassifier())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledCART', Pipeline([('Scaler', StandardScaler()),('CART',DecisionTreeClassifier())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledNB', Pipeline([('Scaler', StandardScaler()),('NB',GaussianNB())])))
pipelines.append(('ScaledSVM', Pipeline([('Scaler', StandardScaler()),('SVM', SVC())])))

results = []
names = []


# Process each dataset in their respective pipelines
for name, model in pipelines:
    kfold = cross_validation.KFold(n=num_instances, n_folds=num_folds, random_state=seed)
    cv_results = cross_validation.cross_val_score(model, X_train, Y_train, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)

TASK: Achieve better than (.3) Precision and (.3) Recall using the test script.¶

  • It is very likely that configuration beyond the default may yield even more accurate models.
  • We'll execute a grid search for the optimal parameter set and display the best candidates.
  • We only search for optimal tuning parameters for those algorithms which have proven worthy to investigate further.

scaler = StandardScaler().fit(X_train)
rescaledX = scaler.transform(X_train)


# Set the parameter values of concern

criterion_values = ['gini', 'entropy']
min_samples_split_values = [1, 2, 3, 4]
splitter_values = ['best', 'random']
max_features_values = [7, 9, 12, 'auto', 'sqrt', 'log2']
class_weight_values = [{1: 1} , {0: .5}]
                                                              # Grid
param_grid = dict(criterion=criterion_values,min_samples_split=min_samples_split_values,splitter=splitter_values,
                 max_features=max_features_values,class_weight=class_weight_values)   
model_DTC = DecisionTreeClassifier()                          # Model


# KFOLD Validation Execution & Grid Search

kfold = cross_validation.KFold(n=num_instances, n_folds=num_folds, random_state=seed)
grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=model_DTC, param_grid=param_grid, scoring=scoring, cv=kfold)
grid_result = grid.fit(rescaledX, Y_train)


# OutPut Results:

print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_)), "\n"
for params, mean_score, scores in grid_result.grid_scores_:
    print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (scores.mean(), scores.std(), params))

Ensemble Methods - Benchmarking¶

Another way that we can improve the performance of algorithms on this problem is by using ensemble methods.

  • In this section we will evaluate four different ensemble machine learning algorithms, two boosting and two bagging methods:

Boosting Methods: - Building multiple models (typically of the same type) from difierent subsamples of the training dataset.

  • AdaBoost (AB)

  • Gradient Boosting (GBM)

Bagging Methods: - Building multiple models (typically of the same type) each of which learns to fix the prediction errors of a prior model in the sequence of models.

  • Random Forests (RF)

  • Extra Trees (ET)

  • Bagging (BG)

We will use the same test harness as before, 10-fold cross validation.

  • NOTE: No data standardization is used in this case because all four ensemble algorithms are based on decision trees that are less sensitive to fluctuations in data distributions.
In [89]:
# Benchmarking Ensemble Methods

ensembles = []
ensembles.append(('AB', AdaBoostClassifier()))
ensembles.append(('GBM', GradientBoostingClassifier()))
ensembles.append(('RF', RandomForestClassifier()))
ensembles.append(('ET', ExtraTreesClassifier()))
ensembles.append(('BG', BaggingClassifier()))
results = []
names = []


# KFOLD Validation Execution & Grid Search

for name, model in ensembles:
    kfold = cross_validation.KFold(n=num_instances, n_folds=num_folds, random_state=seed)
    cv_results = cross_validation.cross_val_score(model, X_train, Y_train, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: MEAN: %f STD: (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)
    
# Running the example provides the following accuracy scores.

AB: MEAN: 0.820513 STD: (0.152559)
GBM: MEAN: 0.829487 STD: (0.107578)
RF: MEAN: 0.859615 STD: (0.103935)
ET: MEAN: 0.875641 STD: (0.086203)
BG: MEAN: 0.844872 STD: (0.097377)

We can see that both boosting techniques provide strong accuracy scores with default configurations.

  • We should plot the distribution of accuracy scores across the cross validation folds.

Grid Search For Tuning the ExtraTreesClassifier (ETC)¶

The ExtraTreesClassifier can really benefit from choosing the right values for key parameters and warrants a proper grid search to unearth a few sets of them.

In [96]:
# Grid Search for ExtraTreesClassifier

# Parameter List Construction:

n_estimators_values  = [6,8,10,12,14]
criterion_values = ['gini', 'entropy']
min_samples_split_values = [1, 2, 3, 4]
max_features_values = [7, 9, 12, 'auto', 'sqrt', 'log2']
class_weight_values = [{1: 1} , {0: .5}]


# Grid
param_grid = dict(criterion=criterion_values,min_samples_split=min_samples_split_values,n_estimators=n_estimators_values,
                 max_features=max_features_values,class_weight=class_weight_values) 

# Model
model_ETC = ExtraTreesClassifier()                          

# KFold Input constants
num_folds = 10
num_instances = len(X_train)
seed = 7

# KFOLD Validation:
kfold = cross_validation.KFold(n=num_instances, n_folds=num_folds, random_state=seed)
grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=model_ETC, param_grid=param_grid, scoring=scoring, cv=kfold)
grid_result = grid.fit(rescaledX, Y_train)


# OutPut Results:
print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_)), "\n"
for params, mean_score, scores in grid_result.grid_scores_:
    print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (scores.mean(), scores.std(), params))

    
# SIMPLE ACCURACY SCORE
model_ETC.fit(rescaledX, Y_train)
# estimate accuracy on validation dataset
rescaledValidationX = scaler.transform(X_validation)
predictions = model_ETC.predict(rescaledValidationX)
print "\nSimple Accuracy Score: ", accuracy_score(Y_validation, predictions)

The following performance measures that can give more insight into the accuracy of the model than traditional classification accuracy:

  • Confusion Matrix: A breakdown of predictions into a table showing correct predictions (the diagonal) and the types of incorrect predictions made (what classes incorrect predictions were assigned).
  • Precision: A measure of a classifiers exactness.
  • Recall: A measure of a classifiers completeness
  • F1 Score (or F-score): A weighted average of precision and recall.

(1) Load Test Algorithm¶

This next cell loads the testing code, it only needs to be run once, there is not output.

In [103]:
#!/usr/bin/pickle

""" a basic script for importing student's POI identifier,
    and checking the results that they get from it 
 
    requires that the algorithm, dataset, and features list
    be written to my_classifier.pkl, my_dataset.pkl, and
    my_feature_list.pkl, respectively

    that process should happen at the end of poi_id.py
"""

import pickle
import sys
from sklearn.cross_validation import StratifiedShuffleSplit
sys.path.append("../tools/")
from feature_format import featureFormat, targetFeatureSplit



PERF_FORMAT_STRING = "\
\tAccuracy: {:>0.{display_precision}f}\tPrecision: {:>0.{display_precision}f}\t\
Recall: {:>0.{display_precision}f}\tF1: {:>0.{display_precision}f}\tF2: {:>0.{display_precision}f}"
RESULTS_FORMAT_STRING = "\tTotal predictions: {:4d}\tTrue positives: {:4d}\tFalse positives: {:4d}\
\tFalse negatives: {:4d}\tTrue negatives: {:4d}"



def test_classifier(clf, dataset, feature_list, folds = 1000):
    data = featureFormat(dataset, feature_list, sort_keys = True)
    labels, features = targetFeatureSplit(data)
    cv = StratifiedShuffleSplit(labels, folds, random_state = 42)
    true_negatives = 0
    false_negatives = 0
    true_positives = 0
    false_positives = 0
    for train_idx, test_idx in cv: 
        features_train = []
        features_test  = []
        labels_train   = []
        labels_test    = []
        for ii in train_idx:
            features_train.append( features[ii] )
            labels_train.append( labels[ii] )
        for jj in test_idx:
            features_test.append( features[jj] )
            labels_test.append( labels[jj] )
        
        ### fit the classifier using training set, and test on test set
        clf.fit(features_train, labels_train)
        predictions = clf.predict(features_test)
        for prediction, truth in zip(predictions, labels_test):
            if prediction == 0 and truth == 0:
                true_negatives += 1
            elif prediction == 0 and truth == 1:
                false_negatives += 1
            elif prediction == 1 and truth == 0:
                false_positives += 1
            elif prediction == 1 and truth == 1:
                true_positives += 1
            else:
                print "Warning: Found a predicted label not == 0 or 1."
                print "All predictions should take value 0 or 1."
                print "Evaluating performance for processed predictions:"
                break
    try:
        total_predictions = true_negatives + false_negatives + false_positives + true_positives
        accuracy = 1.0*(true_positives + true_negatives)/total_predictions
        precision = 1.0*true_positives/(true_positives+false_positives)
        recall = 1.0*true_positives/(true_positives+false_negatives)
        f1 = 2.0 * true_positives/(2*true_positives + false_positives+false_negatives)
        f2 = (1+2.0*2.0) * precision*recall/(4*precision + recall)
        print clf
        print PERF_FORMAT_STRING.format(accuracy, precision, recall, f1, f2, display_precision = 5)
        print RESULTS_FORMAT_STRING.format(total_predictions, true_positives, false_positives, false_negatives, true_negatives)
        print ""
    except:
        print "Got a divide by zero when trying out:", clf
        print "Precision or recall may be undefined due to a lack of true positive predicitons."

        
        
CLF_PICKLE_FILENAME = "my_classifier.pkl"
DATASET_PICKLE_FILENAME = "my_dataset.pkl"
FEATURE_LIST_FILENAME = "my_feature_list.pkl"



def dump_classifier_and_data(clf, dataset, feature_list):
    with open(CLF_PICKLE_FILENAME, "w") as clf_outfile:
        pickle.dump(clf, clf_outfile)
    with open(DATASET_PICKLE_FILENAME, "w") as dataset_outfile:
        pickle.dump(dataset, dataset_outfile)
    with open(FEATURE_LIST_FILENAME, "w") as featurelist_outfile:
        pickle.dump(feature_list, featurelist_outfile)

        
        
def load_classifier_and_data():
    with open(CLF_PICKLE_FILENAME, "r") as clf_infile:
        clf = pickle.load(clf_infile)
    with open(DATASET_PICKLE_FILENAME, "r") as dataset_infile:
        dataset = pickle.load(dataset_infile)
    with open(FEATURE_LIST_FILENAME, "r") as featurelist_infile:
        feature_list = pickle.load(featurelist_infile)
    return clf, dataset, feature_list

Question # 1¶

(1) Summarize for us the goal of this project and how machine learning is useful in trying to accomplish it. As part of your answer, give some background on the dataset and how it can be used to answer the project question. Were there any outliers in the data when you got it, and how did you handle those?

[relevant rubric items: data exploration, outlier investigation]

Answer # 1¶

The goal of this project is to detect additional bad guys (aka "persons of interest", POI) by using the Enron data to create a Machine Learning Classifier of a POI which is capable of detecting new POI's with verifiable measures of accuracy, precision, and recall.

Relevant Link: Project Background

The dataset contains email, financial, and labels (indicating POI's) data. The idea is that there is enough multi-dimmensional information contained in those features (and newly engineered ones) to accurately classify new POI's based upon the features of the already classified POI's. Many of the fields required transformation to be useful.

Relevant Link: Quick Data Anlysis One Section

There were most definitely outliers (2) which were removed (dropped entirely from the dataset) to enhance the accuracy of the classifier.

Relevant Link: Outlier Detection & Removal Section

[TOC](#TableOfContents#DocumentationQuestions)

Question # 2¶

(2) What features did you end up using in your POI identifier, and what selection process did you use to pick them? Did you have to do any scaling? Why or why not? As part of the assignment, you should attempt to engineer your own feature that does not come ready-made in the dataset -- explain what feature you tried to make, and the rationale behind it. (You do not necessarily have to use it in the final analysis, only engineer and test it.) [relevant rubric items: create new features, properly scale features, intelligently select feature]

Answer # 2¶

The 15 features used are listed below (in bold), I interrogated two automated feature selectors (Select KBest and Recursive Feature Elimination), and settled on SelectKBest because it provided results which seemed more intuitive.

I provide an analysis of which 15 features were chosen, and the methodology deployed for feature selection below. All of this comes over the backdrop of using an Esemble Algorithm of ExtraTreesClassifier->KNN as the algorithm the POI tester script evaluates.

Additionally, all Precision / Recall results are from runs of the POI script results.

The ranked KBest feature scores are also listed as well as a plot of the precision / recall results used in he selection process.

In the end the nuances of performance were very subtle as they all performed fairly well. I settled on the 15 selected KBest features listed below because they performed the best with the fewest features. I could have gone with far fewer feature without a significant performance hit, but in the interest of having the best possible precision/recall scores I settled on the 15 chosen which provided a Precision of 0.89709, and a Recall of 0.92400.

SVC

  • there are some that don't speciically require it:

    DecisionTreeClassifier

Input scaling is where the data is transformed such that each attribute has a mean value of zero and a standard deviation of one.

  • That way we can get a fair estimation of how each model with standardized data might perform on unseen data.

Question # 4¶

(4) What does it mean to tune the parameters of an algorithm, and what can happen if you dont do this well? How did you tune the parameters of your particular algorithm? (Some algorithms do not have parameters that you need to tune -- if this is the case for the one you picked, identify and briefly explain how you would have done it for the model that was not your final choice or a different model that does utilize parameter tuning, e.g. a decision tree classifier).

[relevant rubric item: tune the algorithm]

Answer # 4¶

Many classification algorithms in SKLearn have (some or many) parameters which govern their behavior in the classification process. Some parameters are very influential and others are only mildly so. In many cases the combinatorics of the number of parameters combined with setup and execution time make a brute force approach to tuning not a viable option. In these cases, we use a parameter search process like a Grid Search, which was my choice, and worked well.

If you choose to not tune your algorithm (accepting all of the defaults), the algorithm will still do it's job, but just not as accurately as possible if given the right parameters for the data it's being used on.

On the other hand, some parameters really need to be tuned wisely, such as "kernel type" for SVN or "min_samples_split" for Decision Tree Classifiers because if they are given a value not within reasonable boundaries then the performance of the algorithm can go from inaccurate, to memory and time hogs for execution.

Question # 5¶

(5) What is validation, and whats a classic mistake you can make if you do it wrong? How did you validate your analysis?

[relevant rubric item: validation strategy]

Answer # 5¶

Validation is the process of verifying or vetting ones algorithm on data it has never seen before in order to check for errors and establish accuracy of the model.

It industry best practices to use a validation hold-out set. This is a sample of the data that we hold back from our analysis and modeling. We use it right at the end of our project to confirm the accuracy of our final model.

It can be considered a smoke test that we can use to see if we have introduced errors and to give us confidence on our estimates of accuracy on unseen data. I will use 80% of the dataset for modeling and hold back 20% for validation.

  • Generally k-fold cross validation is the gold standard for evaluating the performance of a machine learning algorithm on unseen data with k set to 3, 5, or 10.
  • Using a train/test split is good for speed when using a slow algorithm and produces performance estimates with lower bias when using large datasets.

Question # 6¶

(6) Give at least 2 evaluation metrics and your average performance for each of them. Explain an interpretation of your metrics that says something human-understandable about your algorithms performance.

[relevant rubric item: usage of evaluation metrics]

Answer # 6¶

There are many ways to avaluate an algorithm, in particular I have used the following in this project:

  • Mean CrossValidation Score
  • Simple Accuracy Score
  • Confusion Matrix
  • Classification Report

NOTE - The dataset is very small, therefore it is important to use the SKLearn function StratifiedShuffleSplit which uses precision, recall, F1-score and F2-score instead of an explicit hold-out set for validation because there just isn't enough data available for an explicit hold-out validation set and we'd be "unconfident" of the results in that case.

On larger datasets it's preferred to use explicit hold-out sets since it's the gold standard in vetting the performance of algorithms.

  • Note - Since I oversampled (thus adding redundant instances of under represented class variables, it did boost the data set to the point where I could experiment with explicit hold out sets in the core experiments of the classifier creation.
  • Note: - Below I re-list the performance table of all of the classifiers I have investigated for this project and their actual scores in addition to the performance measures for the Ensemble Classifier - ExtraTreesClassifier => KNN that I eventually chose.

The following performance measures that can give more insight into the accuracy of the model than traditional classification accuracy:

  • Confusion Matrix: A breakdown of predictions into a table showing correct predictions (the diagonal) and the types of incorrect predictions made (what classes incorrect predictions were assigned).
  • Precision: A measure of a classifiers exactness, or in plain english, "how useful the search results are". A more specific way of understanding precision is "how many of the selected items are actually relevant in classifying a POI"?
  • Recall: A measure of a classifiers completeness, or in plain english, "how complete the results are". A more specific way of understanding precision is "how many of the relevant items are actually selected which will help better calssify a POI"?
  • F1 Score (or F-score): A weighted average of precision and recall.
  • Simple Accuracy Score: - this is actually the least accurate and informative metric of all of them. It's a good quick and dirty process to give a gross measurement, but there are other metrics which absolutely must be used for credibility sake.
